<p>
  it starts with netflix. then amazon prime. then spotify. then disney+ because the kids want it. then apple tv+ came free with the phone, but that offer expired and it's still billing. then you added now tv for the football. then youtube premium because the ads got unbearable.
</p>

<p>
  six services later, you're paying £78/month for content you watch maybe 8 hours a week combined. that's £936 a year — or £9,360 over a decade.
</p>

<h3>the creep is the point</h3>

<p>
  streaming services are priced to feel individually cheap. £7.99 here, £10.99 there — each is less than a takeaway coffee habit. but the model is built on aggregation. netflix knows you'll subscribe. disney knows you'll subscribe. the goal isn't to be your only service — it's to be one of six.
</p>

<p>
  the churn rate ceiling is about 5% per month across the industry. that means 95% of subscribers stay subscribed every single month, even if they watch nothing. the average uk household now pays for 3.4 streaming services, up from 1.5 in 2019.
</p>

<h3>the annual plan discount trap</h3>

<p>
  many services offer 15–20% off if you pay annually instead of monthly. but the real saving comes from canceling services you don't use, not prepaying for ones you might. paying annually locks you in — you can't cancel for a refund. and when the year ends, the auto-renewal hits at the full price.
</p>

<p>
  perch. recommendation: audit your streaming subscriptions quarterly. if you didn't watch anything on a service in the last 30 days, cancel it. you can always resubscribe when the next season of the show you care about drops. you'll save roughly £200–400/year and not miss anything you would have watched.
</p>
